article.description: Nykesha Sales had 17 points and the Connecticut Sun avenged their only loss with a 73-63 win over the Detroit Shock on Saturday night in Uncasville, Conn.
article.headline: Connecticut avenges only loss of season
article.linkText: Sales' 17 leads Sun to double-digit win over Shock
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Connecticut managed to keep
top-rebounding Detroit off the boards just long enough Saturday
night.

Nykesha Sales had 17 points and three steals, leading the Sun to
a 73-63 win over Detroit to avenge their only loss of the season.

The Shock, who have the league's top rebounder in Cheryl Ford
and lead the WNBA with 36.9 boards a game, dominated inside but
found themselves playing from behind all night.

"I thought our initial defense was terrific," Connecticut
coach Mike Thibault said. "We just did a poor job of blocking out
for two stretches. It was a great win."

Taj McWilliams-Franklin added 14 points and 10 rebounds as the
Sun (7-1) ran their win streak to a franchise-best seven games.

And early on, they made it look easy.

The inside-outside tandem of 7-foot-2 Margo Dydek and Sales
helped the Sun race to a 16-0 lead in the first 6 minutes. Dydek
had four points and three blocks in the run and Sales added seven
points and a steal. But foul trouble forced Dydek to the bench a
minute later and the Shock (5-4) began dominating inside.

Ayana Walker hit three straight baskets, all off offensive
rebounds, and the rally was on. Detroit, which outscored the Sun
16-9 over the final 10 minutes of the half, got within 31-27 on a
pair of free throws by Barbara Ferris with 1:30 left. With Dydek
out, the Shock outrebounded the Sun 25-14 in the half and trailed
just 32-27 at the break.

"That's just the history of their team. Detroit is a very
aggressive team that works hard on the boards," Sales said. "That
was expected. They were getting second chances on every
possession."

Dydek returned to start the second period, and so did the Sun's
transition game. Connecticut led by as many as 16 points in the
second half and got a big boost from its bench. Reserves Asjha
Jones and Brooke Wyckoff combined for 21 points. Wyckoff, who leads
the WNBA in 3-point shooting percentage (.727) was 3-of-3 from
behind the arc.

"We just regrouped and blocked out and got the job done,"
Jones said.

Reserve Chandi Jones, the only Shock player in double figures,
had nine of her 11 points in the second half to keep Detroit close.
The Shock got within six with 1:36 left, but Connecticut shot 7 for
8 from the line to seal the win.

"We shot poorly," Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer said. "We
weren't able to get into a rhythm offensively. We went into long
stretches without scoring and we can't do that. We need people to
step up."

The Shock have been without All-Star forward Swin Cash, who is
recovering from offseason knee surgery. Cash did travel with the
team, returning to Connecticut, where she starred in college at
UConn.

"She's our captain and our leader," Laimbeer said. "She loves
to be on the floor but unfortunately now she can't, so any support
she can lend is a positive."

The Sun remain unbeaten at home, winning four this season and
nine overall dating to last season. They lost 78-67 at Detroit in
the season opener on May 21.

Walker finished with nine points and tied a career-best with 10
boards for Detroit, which outrebounded the Sun 45-35 and outscored
them 30-18 in the paint.

Lindsay Whalen led the Sun with six assists and a career-high
nine rebounds. Dydek played just 19 minutes and finished with five
rebounds, four points and four blocked shots.

"The Sun have a lot more team chemistry than the last time we
faced them," Chandi Jones said. "It was a dog fight between two
good teams tonight and this time Connecticut came out on top."
